\begin{align*}
|K^0(t)\rangle &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left[e^{-i m_L c^2 t/\hbar} |K_L\rangle + e^{-i m_S c^2 t/\hbar}|K_S\rangle\right] \\
|\bar{K}^0(t)\rangle &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left[e^{-i m_L c^2 t/\hbar} |K_L\rangle - e^{-i m_S c^2 t/\hbar}|K_S\rangle\right]
\end{align*}
Using this, the probabilities can be found as:
\begin{align*}
P_0(t) &= \langle K^0 | K^0(t) \rangle = \frac{1}{2}\left[e^{-{\rm i} \frac{m_L}{\hbar}ct} + e^{-{\rm i} \frac{m_S}{\hbar} ct}\right]\cdot \frac{1}{2}\left[e^{{\rm i} \frac{m_L}{\hbar}ct} + e^{{\rm i} \frac{m_S}{\hbar} ct}\right] \\
&= \frac{1}{4}\left[1 + \cos(\omega_{LS}t)\right], \,\,\, {\rm where} \,\,\, \omega_{LS} = \frac{m_L - m_S}{\hbar}c
\end{align*}
Similarly,
\begin{align*}
\bar{P}_0(t) &= \langle \bar{K}^0 | \bar{K}^0(t) \rangle = \frac{1}{2}\left[e^{-{\rm i} \frac{m_L}{\hbar}ct} - e^{-{\rm i} \frac{m_S}{\hbar} ct}\right]\cdot \frac{1}{2}\left[e^{{\rm i} \frac{m_L}{\hbar}ct} - e^{{\rm i} \frac{m_S}{\hbar} ct}\right] \\
&= \frac{1}{4}\left[1 - \cos(\omega_{LS}t)\right]
\end{align*}
Therefore, the difference between the probabilities is:
\begin{align*}
P_0(t) - \bar{P}_0(t) &= \frac{1}{4}\left[\cos(\omega_{LS}t) - (-\cos(\omega_{LS}t))\right] \\
&= \boxed{\frac{1}{2} \sin (\omega_{LS} t)}.
\end{align*}

This oscillates between -1 and 1 with a frequency given by the energy difference $(m_L - m_S)/\hbar$. The decay rates $\gamma_L, \gamma_S$ do not feature in this expression; they will appear when one considers the amplitudes of these oscillations, which are dampened by the exponential decay of the respective $K_L, K_S$ states. 

