We start from the given action of the ladder operators on an arbitrary state $|j, m\rangle$:
\begin{align*}
    J_+ |j, j-1\rangle &= \hbar \sqrt{j(j+1)} ~|j, j\rangle \\
    J_- |j, j\rangle &= \hbar \sqrt{j(j+1)-j^2} ~|j, j-1\rangle = \hbar \sqrt{j}~|j, j-1\rangle
\end{align*}
Now we want to express the states $|j, j-1\rangle$ in terms of our basis states $|l, m_l; s, m_s\rangle$. We denote this basis transformation as:
$$
|j, j-1\rangle = \sum_{m_l, m_s}\langle l, m_l; s, m_s | j, j-1\rangle ~|l, m_l; s, m_s\rangle
$$
To solve for the expansion coefficients $\langle l, m_l; s, m_s | j, j-1\rangle$, we operate both sides of the equation with the lowering operator $J_-$ and use its action derived above together with the fact that $J_- |l, m_l; s, m_s\rangle = \hbar \sqrt{s(s+1)-m_s(m_s-1)} ~|l, m_l; s, m_s-1\rangle$:
\begin{align*}
    \hbar \sqrt{j}~\sum_{m_l, m_s} \langle l, m_l; s, m_s | j, j-1\rangle ~|l, m_l; s, m_s-1\rangle 
    &= J_- |j, j-1\rangle\\
    &= \hbar \sqrt{j(j-1)} ~|j, j-2\rangle
\end{align*}
For the left hand side, we simply substitute $m_s-1 \rightarrow m_s$ since $m_s$ can only take on the values $\tfrac{1}{2}$ or $-\tfrac{1}{2}$:
\begin{align*}
    \hbar \sqrt{j}~\sum_{m_l, m_s} \langle l, m_l; s, m_s | j, j-1\rangle ~\sqrt{s(s+1)-m_s^2} ~|l, m_l; s, m_s\rangle 
    &= \hbar \sqrt{j(j-1)} ~|j, j-2\rangle
\end{align*}
Comparing both sides, we see that the states $|l, m_l; s, \tfrac{1}{2}\rangle$ have a non-zero overlap with $|j, j-1\rangle$, i.e.,
\begin{equation*}
    \langle l, m_l; \tfrac{1}{2} | j, j-1\rangle \neq 0 ~~\Leftrightarrow~~ j=l+\tfrac{1}{2}
\end{equation*}
The square root factors simplify and we arrive at:
\begin{align*}
    |j, j-1\rangle &= \sqrt{\frac{j}{s(s+1)}}~|l,\,m_l;\, \tfrac{1}{2}\rangle && \text{for } j=l+\tfrac{1}{2}\\
    &\Rightarrow ~~~~~~~~|j,\, j-\tfrac{1}{2}\rangle = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2s+1}}~|l,\,m_l;\, \tfrac{1}{2}\rangle && \text{for } j=l+\tfrac{1}{2}
\end{align*}
which is the desired result. Note that the condition $j=l+\tfrac{1}{2}$ implies that $m=\tfrac{1}{2}-l$ indeed.

Therefore, the solution is:
$$
\boxed{|l,-\tfrac{1}{2}\rangle = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2l+1}}~|l,\,m_l;\,\tfrac{1}{2}\rangle}.
$$

Let's analyze each scenario and provide a qualitative graph for each:

1. (a) Slit A open, slit B closed:
The graph will show a peak centered on the position corresponding to slit A. It will be a sharp maximum, indicating a high intensity of electrons hitting the screen directly behind slit A, and essentially zero elsewhere. The graph would look like a normal distribution curve with a single peak.

2. (b) Slit B open, slit A closed:
Similar to part (a), but now the peak will be centered on the position corresponding to slit B. All electrons will be concentrated in this region, forming a sharp maxiumum.

3. (c) Both slits open:
Now we'll see two peaks, one corresponding to each slit. The graph will have a central minimum between the two peaks. The shape will resemble two normal distribution curves added together. Each peak corresponds to the probability distribution of electrons emerging from each respective slit.

4. (d) Stern-Gerlach apparatus polarizes the spins:
With the Spin-Gerlach apparatus, the electron spin is now aligned. We'll still see two peaks, but their heights will not necessarily be equal. The peak corresponding to slit A will depend on the fact that only electrons with $\uparrow\uparrow$ spin can get through. The other slit allows electrons with $\downarrow\downarrow$ spin. The graph will reflect this spin-dependent transmission. 

5. (e) Different spin projections allowed in each slit:
This is similar to having two slits, but now the peaks will be further skewed due to the specific spin configurations required for an electron to pass through each slit. The peak corresponding to slit A will be for $\uparrow\frac{1}{2}$ spin projection, while slit B will allow electrons with $\uparrow\downarrow$ spin projection. 

