(a) The eigenvalues of a particle in an infinite square well of width $b$ are given by the discretized energies: 

$$E_n = \dfrac{n^2 \hbar^2 \pi^2}{2mb^2}, \quad n=1,2,3,...$$

And the corresponding normalized eigenfunctions are: 

$$\psi_n(x) = \sqrt{\dfrac{2}{b}}\,\sin\left(\dfrac{n\pi x}{b}\right), \quad 0 \le x \le b.$$

(b) For the small perturbation $V_1(x) = \epsilon \sin \dfrac{\pi x}{b}$, we can use first-order perturbation theory. The energy shift of the $n^{th}$ excited state is given by:

\begin{align*}
\Delta E_n & = \langle \psi_n | V_1 | \psi_n \rangle \\
& = \epsilon \left| \int_0^b \psi_n^*(x) \sin\left( \dfrac{\pi x}{b} \right) \psi_n(x) dx \right| \\
& = \epsilon \cdot \begin{cases}
0, & \text{if } n \text{ is even} \\
\dfrac{2}{\pi} \sqrt{\dfrac{2}{b}} \neq 0, & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}.
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

Therefore, only the odd parity states are affected, and the energy shift is proportional to $\epsilon$.

(c) We will assume that the ground state is the unperturbed $n=1$ state, which is the first excited state within our original well. To find the probability of finding the particle in the first excited state (now shifted to energy $E_1 + \Delta E_1$) at time $t$, we need to calculate the survival amplitude:

\begin{align*}
A(t) & = \langle \psi_1 | e^{-{iHt}/{\hbar}} | \psi_1 \rangle \\
& = \langle \psi_1 | e^{-{i(E_1+\Delta E_1)t/\hbar}} | \psi_1 \rangle \\
& = e^{-i(E_1+\Delta E_1)t/\hbar} \quad (\text{as }\psi_1 \text{ is real})\\
\There P(|\text{first exc.}|t)&=\left|\langle \psi_1 | e^{-{iHt}/{\hbar}} | \psi_1 \rangle \right|^2 = 1.
\end{align*}

So, the probability of remaining in the first excited state is a constant 1.

For the second excited state ($n=2$), the energy shift is also non-zero according to part (b). However, because $V_2$ depends on time, we cannot simply carry out the calculation as before. We'll use the general time-dependent perturbation theory formula:

\begin{align*}
P(n=2,t) &= |\langle \psi_2 | e^{{-\frac{i}{\hbar}}\int_{0}^t H'(t')dt'} | \psi_1 \rangle|^2 \\
&= \left| \sum_\alpha \dfrac{\langle \psi_2 | H'(t) | \psi_\alpha \rangle \langle \psi_\alpha | \psi_1 \rangle}{E_1 - E_\alpha} \left[e^{-{\frac{i}{\hbar}}\left((E_1-E_\alpha)t-\int_0^t E_\alpha dt'\right)\right]\right|^2 \\
&\approx \left| \dfrac{\langle \psi_2 | V_2(t) | \psi_1 \rangle}{\Delta E_1} \right|^2 \\
&= \left| \lambda \sqrt{\dfrac{2}{b}} \int_0^b \left( x - \dfrac{b}{2} \right) \sin\left( \dfrac{\pi x}{b} \right) \sin\left( \dfrac{2\pi x}{b} \right) \cos(\omega t) dx \right|^2 \\
&= \dfrac{8\lambda^2}{49\pi^2} \left( 1 - \cos(2\omega t) \right),
\end{align*}
where we've used the integral $\int_0^b \left( x - \dfrac{b}{2} \right) \sin(\alpha \pi x/b) \sin(\beta \pi x /b) dx$, which can be derived using integration by parts twice.

Therefore, the probability oscillates between $\dfrac{8\lambda^2}{49\pi^2}$ and 0 as a function of time.

\begin{equation*}
\framed{$\displaystyle P(\text{second exc.}) = \dfrac{8\lambda^2}{49\pi^2} \left( 1 - \cos(2\omega t) \right)$}
\end{equation*}
